snippet.textDisplay:
4K TV adoption has been sluggish because most people can't tell the difference between HD and 4K...and they think their 720p or 1080p TV is good enough. I know I feel that way based on the science of vision and the fact that HD broadcast TV is in 720p or 1080i. When my 1080p TV goes out at some point in the future, I'll go 4K, but I feel no need to upgrade anytime soon.

I have a 4K monitor, but that's a whole different use case. That's more screen real estate for multitasking and photo editing...not to mention editing the 4K wildlife video I sometimes shoot. Really, the main advantage of shooting in 4K is just to punch in and output in 1080p.

And now they're pushing 8K? Nobody cares.
